</div></div></div><div class="post-21974 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-how-to-become-a-writer tag-audience tag-how-to-be-a-writer tag-reading entry"><img width="820" height="380" src="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/4-Tips-for-Writing-to-the-Right-Audience-820x380.jpg" class="post-image" alt="" srcset="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/4-Tips-for-Writing-to-the-Right-Audience-820x380.jpg 820w, https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/4-Tips-for-Writing-to-the-Right-Audience-389x180.jpg 389w" sizes="(max-width: 820px) 100vw, 820px" /><div class="post-wrap"><div class="post-info"><span class="blue"> <span class="author-img"><img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f6ade23f173b61613026376d4020c416?s=50&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f6ade23f173b61613026376d4020c416?s=100&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' /></span> <span class="date published time" title="2018-02-05T04:00:50+00:00">February 5, 2018</span>  by <span class="author vcard"><span class="fn"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/author/kmweiland/" rel="author">K.M. Weiland &#124; @KMWeiland</a></span></span> <span class="post-comments"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/writing-to-the-right-audience/#comments">73 Comments</a></span>  </span><span class="categories"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/category/how-to-become-a-writer/">How to Become a Writer</a></span></div><h2 class="entry-title"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/writing-to-the-right-audience/" rel="bookmark">4 Tips for Writing to the Right Audience</a></h2> 
<div class="entry-content"><p>Here&#8217;s my somewhat radical idea: Writers don&#8217;t need to know who their audience is. And, yes, I know this goes entirely against popular advice, which encourages (even insists) that beginning authors must know their audience. I&#8217;ve probably even said basically that somewhere or other on this site. You&#8217;re supposed to go so far as to write [&hellip;]</p>
</div></div></div><div class="post-21936 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-how-to-become-a-writer tag-audience tag-how-to-become-a-writer tag-reading entry"><img width="820" height="380" src="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/reading-2605540_19201-820x380.jpg" class="post-image" alt="4 Ways for Writers to Become Better Readers" srcset="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/reading-2605540_19201-820x380.jpg 820w, https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/reading-2605540_19201-389x180.jpg 389w" sizes="(max-width: 820px) 100vw, 820px" /><div class="post-wrap"><div class="post-info"><span class="blue"> <span class="author-img"><img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f6ade23f173b61613026376d4020c416?s=50&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f6ade23f173b61613026376d4020c416?s=100&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' /></span> <span class="date published time" title="2018-01-29T04:00:47+00:00">January 29, 2018</span>  by <span class="author vcard"><span class="fn"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/author/kmweiland/" rel="author">K.M. Weiland &#124; @KMWeiland</a></span></span> <span class="post-comments"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/become-better-readers/#comments">60 Comments</a></span>  </span><span class="categories"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/category/how-to-become-a-writer/">How to Become a Writer</a></span></div><h2 class="entry-title"><a href="https://www.helpingwritersbecomeauthors.com/become-better-readers/" rel="bookmark">4 Ways for Writers to Become Better Readers</a></h2> 
<div class="entry-content"><p>Anyone can read a book, right? We all become better readers just by reading, right? Learning to put letters together into words and understand what they say&#8212;learning to read&#8212;that&#8217;s a learned skill. But once you&#8217;ve pretty much mastered that by fourth grade, you can read anything. There&#8217;s no skill to reading a novel. What is there [&hellip;]</p>
